Previously, the sample wouldn't work well for users who either don't send telemetry/reported properties often or who don't do it at all. This is because the client manager would only attempt to reconnect once it tried to send telemetry/reported properties and failed because the client was closed. This meant that a client could be offline (and missing direct method calls and desired property updates) for a while.

With this rework, the sample will now immediately start reconnecting if a terminal disconnection event occurs regardless of if there is any outgoing telemetry and/or reported properties. None, 'body': '# Context

- **OS and version used:** macOS 12.3.1
- **Java runtime used:** OpenJDK 11.0.11
- **SDK version used:** 2.0.0 / 2.0.1

## Description of the issue
`iot-device-client` 2.0.0 and 2.0.1 define a SLF4J binding as dependency in its parent POM (`iot-device-client-parent`). I assume this is not intended as it can mess up the logging of applications using the dependency. Also `iot-sdk-java` includes the `log4j-slf4j-impl` twice in its dependency management.

## Description of the issue
`iot-device-client` 2.0.0 and 2.0.1 define a SLF4J binding as dependency in its parent POM (`iot-device-client-parent`). I assume this is not intended as it can mess up the logging of applications using the dependency. Also `iot-sdk-java` includes the `log4j-slf4j-impl` twice in its dependency management.

(com.microsoft.azure.sdk.iot:iot-device-client:2.0.1)

- Remove accidentally added dependency on a logging binding library (#1524)

### Bug fixes

- Fix bug where twin/method subscription wasn't cleared when client is closed (#1536)
- Fix IO errors and time outs not being classified as retryable (#1534)
- Fix bug where multiplexed devices didn't persist subscriptions if transport error occurred (#1525)

## Java IotHub Service Client (com.microsoft.azure.sdk.iot:iot-service-client:2.0.1)

- Upgrade Guava and Jackson dependencies (#1529)


https://search.maven.org/artifact/com.microsoft.azure.sdk.iot/iot-device-client/2.0.2/jar

Converting the async twin API uses into sync API uses since we were just blocking on them anyways. Also adding a lot more comments explaining how to keep the versions of your reported properties up to date and what to do when they are out of date and your request fails with "precondition failed"

Previously, the sample wouldn't work well for users who either don't send telemetry/reported properties often or who don't do it at all. This is because the client manager would only attempt to reconnect once it tried to send telemetry/reported properties and failed because the client was closed. This meant that a client could be offline (and missing direct method calls and desired property updates) for a while.

With this rework, the sample will now immediately start reconnecting if a terminal disconnection event occurs regardless of if there is any outgoing telemetry and/or reported properties. The only drawback here is that we now have two threads in the sample which may be confusing. I've created a more robust readme to explain those threads though.

{'push_id': 9653309651, 'size': 2, 'distinct_size': 1, 'ref': 'refs/heads/timtay/guava', 'head': '86a071949c90ee57a1eff03482088631f2624811', 'before': '7b3eae531182527992bfdbe73fb471f1fe1af3c9', 'commits': [{'sha': '24c59ee7ed8d47f730782588a7e27cf35ea10d92', 'author': {'email': 'timtay@microsoft.com', 'name': 'timtay-microsoft'}, 'message': "refactor(sample): Rework reconnection sample a bit (#1535)

Previously, the sample wouldn't work well for users who either don't send telemetry/reported properties often or who don't do it at all. This is because the client manager would only attempt to reconnect once it tried to send telemetry/reported properties and failed because the client was closed. This meant that a client could be offline (and missing direct method calls and desired property updates) for a while.

With this rework, the sample will now immediately start reconnecting if a terminal disconnection event occurs regardless of if there is any outgoing telemetry and/or reported properties. The only drawback here is that we now have two threads in the sample which may be confusing. I've created a more robust readme to explain those threads though.

Also replacing System.out.print calls with log.debug calls so that this code can be more easily copied into a user's application.", 'distinct': False, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/Azure/azure-iot-sdk-java/commits/24c59ee7ed8d47f730782588a7e27cf35ea10d92'}, {'sha': '86a071949c90ee57a1eff03482088631f2624811', 'author': {'email': 'timtay@microsoft.com', 'name': 'timtay-microsoft'}, 'message': "Merge branch 'main' into timtay/guava", 'distinct': True, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/Azure/azure-iot-sdk-java/commits/86a071949c90ee57a1eff03482088631f2624811'}]}

Context

- **OS and version used:** Ubuntu 20.04.4 LTS
- **Java runtime used:** openjdk version "15.0.3" 2021-04-20
- **SDK version used:** 2.0.1

## Description of the issue
Hi, this may be something that I am doing wrong, but I don't actually understand the reason.
I am currently updating my former code from SDK v1 to v2 and I got stuck when trying to update the DeviceTwin properties.
I tried by many different ways (creating a new TwinCollection with only the property I want to update or sending the complete set), but I usually receive an error from the cloud with the code `PRECONDITION_FAILED`.

I tried then to run the `DeviceTwinSample` class from the SDK examples using the same device I was testing my code and still received `PRECONDITION_FAILED`.
I thought that maybe it could be some issue related to my device, as it already had plenty of old properties laying around in its twin dictionary. So I created a new clean IoT Device and, even so, trying to run the sample code always give me the same error.

Looks to me that either is something wrong with the v2 implementation or there is, at least, some step missing from the example class I am using.

Lastly, I saw somewhere (I believe in the IoT Hub Csharp github) that this error proably means that the collection I am sending has an out of date ETag with the patch request. I don't actually understand 100% what this means, but I tried to call `client.getTwin()` everytime that I try to send twin update, and indeed, "forcing" this update works, but it limits how fast I can update the twins as I have to wait for the update to then send the new value.
Also, it doesn't make sense to me having to know the old _reported_ properties that are stored in the cloud in order to send an update to a single value.

Again, I can be doing something wrong, but, if it is the case, I don't see where the mistake could be.

Thank you!

## Code sample exhibiting the issue
Straight trying to run the `DeviceTwinSample` class from the SDK examples with a newly created IoT Device throws me the error.

"Previously, the sample wouldn't work well for users who either don't send telemetry/reported properties often or who don't do it at all. This is because the client manager would only attempt to reconnect once it tried to send telemetry/reported properties and failed because the client was closed. This meant that a client could be offline (and missing direct method calls and desired property updates) for a while.

With this rework, the sample will now immediately start reconnecting if a terminal disconnection event occurs regardless of if there is any outgoing telemetry and/or reported properties. The only drawback here is that we now have two threads in the sample which may be confusing. I've created a more robust readme to explain those threads though.

Also replacing System.out.print calls with log.debug calls so that this code can be more easily copied into a user's application.", 'created_at': '2022-04-14T22:10:57Z', 'updated_at': "Previously, the sample wouldn't work well for users who either don't send telemetry/reported properties often or who don't do it at all. This is because the client manager would only attempt to reconnect once it tried to send telemetry/reported properties and failed because the client was closed. This meant that a client could be offline (and missing direct method calls and desired property updates) for a while.

With this rework, the sample will now immediately start reconnecting if a terminal disconnection event occurs regardless of if there is any outgoing telemetry and/or reported properties. The only drawback here is that we now have two threads in the sample which may be confusing. I've created a more robust readme to explain those threads though.

Also replacing System.out.print calls with log.debug calls so that this code can be more easily copied into a user's application.", 'created_at': '2022-04-14T22:10:57Z', 'updated_at': Connection Status Change Reason Ownership of connectivity Comments
CONNECTED CONNECTED_OK SDK SDK tries to remain connected to the service and can carry out all operation as normal
DISCONNECTED_RETRYING NO_NETWORK SDK When disconnection happens because of any reason (network failures, transient loss of connectivity etc.), SDK makes best attempt to connect back to IotHub. The RetryPolicy applied on the DeviceClient will be used to determine the count of reconnection attempts for retriable errors
COMMUNICATION_ERROR
DISCONNECTED CLIENT_CLOSE Application This is state when SDK was asked to close the connection by application
BAD_CREDENTIAL Supplied credential isn’t good for device to connect to service - Fix the supplied credentials before attempting to reconnect again
EXPIRED_SAS_TOKEN Supplied SAS Token has expired - Fix the supplied SAS token before attempting to reconnect again
COMMUNICATION_ERROR This is the state when SDK landed up in a non-retriable error during communication - Inspect the throwable supplied in the IotHubConnectionStatusChangeCallback to get the stacktrace of the exception
RETRY_EXPIRED This is the state when SDK attempted maximum retries set by the application
- -For status `CLIENT_CLOSE`, `COMMUNICATION_ERROR` and `RETRY_EXPIRED`, the application can attempt to reconnect by closing and opening the client again eg. calling `deviceClient.close();` `deviceClient.open();` in a separate thread. - -We would like to highlight here that a separate thread should be used to call `open()`/ `closeNow()`. These calls should never be made from the same thread in the `IotHubConnectionStatusChangeCallback`. +This sample shows the best practices for handling a device (or module) client using a stateful protocol (AMQPS or MQTT) +over the course of its lifetime. This sample is intended to be a starting point for a user developing a production application +wherein their device client must handle unexpected connection loss events and transient errors such as "Previously, the sample wouldn't work well for users who either don't send telemetry/reported properties often or who don't do it at all. This is because the client manager would only attempt to reconnect once it tried to send telemetry/reported properties and failed because the client was closed. This meant that a client could be offline (and missing direct method calls and desired property updates) for a while. With this rework, the sample will now immediately start reconnecting if a terminal disconnection event occurs regardless of if there is any outgoing telemetry and/or reported properties. The only drawback here is that we now have two threads in the sample which may be confusing. I've created a more robust readme to explain those threads though. Also replacing System.out.print calls with log.debug calls so that this code can be more easily copied into a user's application.", 'created_at': '2022-04-14T22:10:57Z', 'updated_at': "Previously, the sample wouldn't work well for users who either don't send telemetry/reported properties often or who don't do it at all. This is because the client manager would only attempt to reconnect once it tried to send telemetry/reported properties and failed because the client was closed. This meant that a client could be offline (and missing direct method calls and desired property updates) for a while.

With this rework, the sample will now immediately start reconnecting if a terminal disconnection event occurs regardless of if there is any outgoing telemetry and/or reported properties. The only drawback here is that we now have two threads in the sample which may be confusing. I've created a more robust readme to explain those threads though.

Also replacing System.out.print calls with log.debug calls so that this code can be more easily copied into a user's application.", 'created_at': '2022-04-14T22:10:57Z', 'updated_at': {'push_id': 9621044537, 'size': 2, 'distinct_size': 1, 'ref': 'refs/heads/timtay/guava', 'head': 'f12b61bb9d14f4872a1bc538c18b37cbaab6c778', 'before': 'ca7daa9650b535dcacb10bb1f37f9b453be9143c', 'commits': [{'sha': 'd91b47731bde33c3049edbf92f2a6824d92216ec', 'author': {'email': 'timtay@microsoft.com', 'name': 'timtay-microsoft'}, 'message': 'refactor(sample): Refactor device twin sample (#1531)

'active_lock_reason': None, 'body': '# Context

- **OS and version used:** Ubuntu 20.04.4 LTS
- **Java runtime used:** openjdk version "15.0.3" 2021-04-20
- **SDK version used:** 2.0.1

## Description of the issue
Hi, this may be something that I am doing wrong, but I don't actually understand the reason.
I am currently updating my former code from SDK v1 to v2 and I got stuck when trying to update the DeviceTwin properties.
I tried by many different ways (creating a new TwinCollection with only the property I want to update or sending the complete set), but I usually receive an error from the cloud with the code `PRECONDITION_FAILED`.

I tried then to run the `DeviceTwinSample` class from the SDK examples using the same device I was testing my code and still received `PRECONDITION_FAILED`.
I thought that maybe it could be some issue related to my device, as it already had plenty of old properties laying around in its twin dictionary. So I created a new clean IoT Device and, even so, trying to run the sample code always give me the same error.

Looks to me that either is something wrong with the v2 implementation or there is, at least, some step missing from the example class I am using.

Lastly, I saw somewhere (I believe in the IoT Hub Csharp github) that this error proably means that the collection I am sending has an out of date ETag with the patch request. I don't actually understand 100% what this means, but I tried to call `client.getTwin()` everytime that I try to send twin update, and indeed, "forcing" this update works, but it limits how fast I can update the twins as I have to wait for the update to then send the new value.
Also, it doesn't make sense to me having to know the old _reported_ properties that are stored in the cloud in order to send an update to a single value.

Again, I can be doing something wrong, but, if it is the case, I don't see where the mistake could be.

Thank you!

## Code sample exhibiting the issue
Straight trying to run the `DeviceTwinSample` class from the SDK examples with a newly created IoT Device throws me the error.

'milestone': None, 'comments': 13, 'created_at': '2022-02-09T05:50:55Z', 'updated_at': '2022-04-11T18:34:09Z', 'closed_at': None, 'author_association': 'NONE', 'active_lock_reason': None, 'body': "# Context

- **OS and version used:** Ubuntu 20.04
- **Java runtime used:** openjdk 11.0.13 2021-10-19
- **SDK version used:** 1.34.1

## Description of the issue
In version 1.34.1 of the SDK, we performed a test where we temporarily disconnect network connectivity (pulled the ethernet cable). We leave the application running for 2 minutes in this state and then restore network connectivity (ethernet cable reconnected).
We expect that Twin, RPC, and events would resume normal function after network connecitivity is restored.
Instead, we observed that Twin and RPC do not function. Events work do though (queued messages are being sent).
In the logs, we found that exception `AmqpConnectionFramingErrorException` is thrown. Looking at the code, it is a retryable exception.
So we'd expect connection status of `IotHubConnectionStatus.DISCONNECTED_RETRYING`. But instead, we encounter `IotHubConnectionStatus.DISCONNECTED`.

## Code sample exhibiting the issue
Existing samples in this repo should exhibit the issue.

## Console log of the issue
Disconnect occurs at 3:41:09. Exception `AmqpConnectionFramingErrorException` is thrown.
Our application's connection listener is triggered with status `IotHubConnectionStatus.DISCONNECTED` and reason `IotHubConnectionStatusChangeReason.CLIENT_CLOSE`.
We don't attempt to re-instantiate a `DeviceClient` instance, since we expect this to be used for graceful disconnect.

'closed_at': None, 'author_association': 'NONE', 'active_lock_reason': None, 'body': '# Context

- **OS and version used:** Docker container based on alpine 3.15 (eclipse-temurin:17-alpine)
- **Java runtime used:** openjdk version "17.0.1" 2021-10-19
- **SDK version used:** iot-device-client:2.0.1

## Description of the issue
It seems that when the MultiplexingClient is stressed with a lot of registrations/unregistrations the registered devices count is not reliable (**MultiplexingClient.getRegisteredDeviceCount()**). 
It causes exception on new registrations.

I added some debug traces. because SDK shadows root cause, there's may be an improvement to do.

***IotHubTransport.java - line 988***
```
                if (deviceRegistrationException != null)
                {
                    if (registrationException == null)
                    {
                        log.error("***********************************");
                        deviceRegistrationException.printStackTrace();
                        log.error("***********************************");
                        registrationException = new MultiplexingClientRegistrationException("Failed to register one or more devices to the multiplexed connection.");
                    }

                    registrationException.addRegistrationException(deviceId, deviceRegistrationException);

                    // Since the registration failed, need to remove the device from the list of multiplexed devices
                    ClientConfiguration configThatFailedToRegister = this.deviceClientConfigs.remove(deviceId);
                    this.multiplexedDeviceConnectionStates.remove(deviceId);
                    ((AmqpsIotHubConnection) this.iotHubTransportConnection).unregisterMultiplexedDevice(configThatFailedToRegister, false);
                }
```
On the stack trace below, at the last line, the first 480 is the device count according to my internal counter and the second 480 is the device count according to the SDK via **MultiplexingClient.getRegisteredDeviceCount()**.
But the IoT Hub has reach the 1000 device connections limit.

Thanks for your help.

'closed_at': None, 'author_association': 'NONE', 'active_lock_reason': None, 'body': '# Context

- **OS and version used:** Docker container based on alpine 3.15 (eclipse-temurin:17-alpine)
- **Java runtime used:** openjdk version "17.0.1" 2021-10-19
- **SDK version used:** iot-device-client:2.0.1

## Description of the issue
It seems that when the MultiplexingClient is stressed with a lot of registrations/unregistrations the registered devices count is not reliable (**MultiplexingClient.getRegisteredDeviceCount()**). 
It causes exception on new registrations.

I added some debug traces. because SDK shadows root cause, there's may be an improvement to do.

***IotHubTransport.java - line 988***
```
                if (deviceRegistrationException != null)
                {
                    if (registrationException == null)
                    {
                        log.error("***********************************");
                        deviceRegistrationException.printStackTrace();
                        log.error("***********************************");
                        registrationException = new MultiplexingClientRegistrationException("Failed to register one or more devices to the multiplexed connection.");
                    }

                    registrationException.addRegistrationException(deviceId, deviceRegistrationException);

                    // Since the registration failed, need to remove the device from the list of multiplexed devices
                    ClientConfiguration configThatFailedToRegister = this.deviceClientConfigs.remove(deviceId);
                    this.multiplexedDeviceConnectionStates.remove(deviceId);
                    ((AmqpsIotHubConnection) this.iotHubTransportConnection).unregisterMultiplexedDevice(configThatFailedToRegister, false);
                }
```
On the stack trace below, at the last line, the first 480 is the device count according to my internal counter and the second 480 is the device count according to the SDK via **MultiplexingClient.getRegisteredDeviceCount()**.
But the IoT Hub has reach the 1000 device connections limit.

Thanks for your help.

The proton-j reactor powering the multiplexed connection still had references to the various amqp handler objects used in our SDK even after the client using each of these handlers had been unregistered. By clearing the handlers from the reactor, the JVM is free to garbage collect these handlers

Also fix a few small state maps that weren't kept up to date whenever a client was unregistered from a muxed connection

#1478", 'distinct': False, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/Azure/azure-iot-sdk-java/commits/1a3b02bd10928ddebccc9a1fee77f23eab3e41dc'}, {'sha': '26e53bb7d2c2a4aa6368e2394f9c801dcc2272c1', 'author': {'email': 'timtay@microsoft.com', 'name': 'timtay-microsoft'}, 'message': "refactor(iot-dev): Rework how reconnection is done (#1491)

Previously, the amqp/mqtt layer would spawn a thread each time a disconnect occurred. For mux scenarios, this meant 1 thread spawned per device session lost and 1 thread spawned if the mux connection as a whole was lost. This didn't scale well and caused some interesting race conditions if a mux-client level retry happened at the same time as a device session retry.

With this change, now there is a dedicated thread that is woken up each time a disconnect happens that handles all disconnected connections and muxed device sessions.

The biggest benefit here is the scale of handling cases where many muxed device sessions are lost at once. Another big benefit is the abilitiy to abandon device session specific retry if the muxed connection is lost and instead reopen the whole connection. By not have so many retry threads floating around, we also cut down on race conditions that were prevalent when a muxed connection retry start happens shortly after a device session retry starts.

In refactoring this code, I have also fixed a bug where a multiplexed device session would erroneously report DISCONNECTED when it was closed as part of the broader multiplexing client's reconnection attempt.", 'distinct': False, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/Azure/azure-iot-sdk-java/commits/26e53bb7d2c2a4aa6368e2394f9c801dcc2272c1'}, {'sha': '2ce600dccd264487cf7ab34e2afd176806d8be67', 'author': {'email': 'timtay@microsoft.com', 'name': 'timtay-microsoft'}, 'message': "refactor(e2e): Mark a c2d test as standard tier only (#1495)

Context

- **OS and version used:** Ubuntu 20.04
- **Java runtime used:** openjdk 11.0.13 2021-10-19
- **SDK version used:** 1.34.1

## Description of the issue
In version 1.34.1 of the SDK, we performed a test where we temporarily disconnect network connectivity (pulled the ethernet cable). We leave the application running for 2 minutes in this state and then restore network connectivity (ethernet cable reconnected).
We expect that Twin, RPC, and events would resume normal function after network connecitivity is restored.
Instead, we observed that Twin and RPC do not function. Events work do though (queued messages are being sent).
In the logs, we found that exception `AmqpConnectionFramingErrorException` is thrown. Looking at the code, it is a retryable exception.
So we'd expect connection status of `IotHubConnectionStatus.DISCONNECTED_RETRYING`. But instead, we encounter `IotHubConnectionStatus.DISCONNECTED`.

## Code sample exhibiting the issue
Existing samples in this repo should exhibit the issue.

## Console log of the issue
Disconnect occurs at 3:41:09. Exception `AmqpConnectionFramingErrorException` is thrown.
Our application's connection listener is triggered with status `IotHubConnectionStatus.DISCONNECTED` and reason `IotHubConnectionStatusChangeReason.CLIENT_CLOSE`.
We don't attempt to re-instantiate a `DeviceClient` instance, since we expect this to be used for graceful disconnect.

### Bug fixes

- Fix bug where synchronous operations did not throw an exception if it received an unsuccessful status code (#1512)
- Fix bug where AMQP connections did not map AmqpLinkMessageSizeExceededException to REQUEST_ENTITY_TOO_LARGE (#1512)
- Fix stack traces for synchronous methods not including the synchronous method call itself (#1512)
- Fix bug where multiplexing client did not cancel queued or sent packets for a device when it is unregistered (#1503)


## Java IotHub Service Client (com.microsoft.azure.sdk.iot:iot-service-client:2.0.1)

### Bug fixes

- Fix a bug where numeric configuration values were always serialized and deserialized as floats even if they were integers (#1510)
- Fix bug where configuration content was not serialized correctly (#1510)
- Fix bug where SDK rejected deserialized registry device instances with no authentication details (#1508)
- Fix bug where twin metadata isn't given to user even when it was received from service (#1516)

```org.apache.commons:comons-lang3``` library in recent versions and this service client package takes a dependency on it. Can you try the lower dependency version of commons-lang3 for your project?

```gradle
dependencies {
    implementation ('com.microsoft.azure.sdk.iot:iot-service-client:1.31.0') {
        exclude(group = "com.apache.commons", module = "commons-lang3")
   }

    implementation ('com.apache.commons:commons-lang3:3.6')
}
```', 'reactions': {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/Azure/azure-iot-sdk-java/issues/comments/1090463188/reactions', 'total_count': 0, '+1': 0, '-1': 0, 'laugh': 0, 'hooray': 0, 'confused': 0, 'heart': 0, 'rocket': 0, 'eyes': 0}, 'performed_via_github_app': None}}
